  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT53-kilavi">varaivu nīṭṭittavaḻit tōḻi talaimakaṟku uraittatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Declared to HIM by the confidante when [he] delayed marriage.</p>
          </div>



        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT53">
<l>                emmaṇaṅ kiṉavē makiḻna muṉṟi</l>
<l>                ṉaṉaimutir puṉkiṉ pūttāḻ veṇmaṇal</l>
<l>                vēlaṉ puṉainta veṟiyayar kaḷantoṟuñ</l>
<l>                cennel vāṉpori citaṟi yaṉṉa</l>
<l>                vekkar naṇṇiya vemmūr viyaṉṟuṟai</l>
<l>                nēriṟai muṉkai paṟṟic</l>
<l>                cūrara makaḷirō ṭuṟṟa cūḷē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
             <l>The oaths made in front of<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">-oṭu</term> must be understood here in the sense of "in the presence of". Another possibility (D.G.) would be "together [with the names of] awe-inspiring celestial damsels". Unfortunately we do not even know whether they have names.</note> dreadful celestial women,</l>
             <l>tormented us, delightful man,</l>
             <l rend="indent">when you had grasped [my] forearm with tender joints</l>
             <l rend="indent">at the wide ghat of our village close to the dunes</l>
             <l rend="indent">with white sand, on which hang down the flowers of the Puṉku</l>
             <l rend="indent4">with ripe buds</l>
             <l rend="indent">in the front-yard, like bright grains together with red rice,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cennel</term> is explained by TVG (as by Cām.) to be not red rice but a particular sort of rice (an especially good one). Is it possible that the gist of the image is that red flowers are coming down into the white sand just as on the Veṟi ground red rice contrasts with bright corn? But to make an argument out of that one would have to know the colour of Puṉku blossoms.</note></l>
             <l rend="indent">strewn in all grounds where [they] dance the Veṟi,<note place="foot">It is difficult to tell whether <term xml:lang="ta">ayar</term> is used here in a semantically strong sense, or rather as a copula for the Veṟi dance, i.e. a floor for the Veṟi.</note></l>
             <l rend="indent2">
                <choice>
                    <seg>practised</seg>
                    <seg>adorned</seg>
                </choice>
                by Murukaṉ's priest.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">puṉai</term> otherwise is clearly used in the sense of "adorn", so perhaps puṉainta should not be connected with the dance, but with the place.</note>
             </l>
                </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
